1) With Kunark, they increased the resist rates for all types of Resistences ;(fire, cold, magic, poison) for 50+ encounters. This meant that the wizard's primary weapon was severely hampered. Enter the Lure line which was probably the latest and best Wizard balance ... the idea being that a Wizard could percentagewise land more damage than she normally would using these spells. By some logic, Lures cost more mana and do less damage than the normal spells in order to acquire this ability.<br>
2) In Velious they significantly increased the hit points of 50+ mobs to make battles more challenging and last longer. Combine high resist rates with high hit point mobs and high mana usage/low damage output for Lures in Velious and we can see the problems arising. Wizard effectiveness in the 50+ game drops like a rock on the continent.<br>
<br>
Remedies to these combinations of high hitpoints, high resistances, high mana usage/low damage for lures are not adequately addressed in the original line of Velious spells for Wizards. We were (and are) expected to continue with the original Kunark line of Lure spells with the addition of a lower 44th lvl one (Enticement of Flame). Enter the Bane spells, which are reportedly unresistable, do significant damage and at moderate mana cost (400). Following this logic we should consider Banes extremely high level Lures since their premise is the same. <br>
<br>
Balance thoughts following Verant logic:<br>
<br>
Making Lures more effective for Velious mobs say by decreasing mana usage or damage total will upset the balance of the 50+ Kunark game.<br>
Lowering resist rates for 50+ mobs in Velious and Kunark will make all casters more effective, not just wizards, upsetting the 50+ game everywhere.<br>
<br>
My suggestion considering these two problems is that Verant should make the Lure lines more of an inherent Wizard ability and examine the impact this will have on 50+ Kunark and Velious encounters, which I believe will be to make the Wizard more of an asset than a liability on both continents. What do I mean by inherent? In the current Lure spell line, the mana/damage ratio is very low which makes me believe that casting these spells is Difficult for a wizard. Why is that? Perhaps an enchanter or mage might find this kind of spell difficult but to Wizards this should be innate. Since the wizard is master of offensive spells, ramp up damage to mana in line with other wizard spells. Since the Lure line is the only direct damage line of spells the wizard gets post 50, it is by default the preferred attack spell.<br>
Thus:<br>
44th lvl: Enticement of Flame <br>
DD Fire 360: mana 180 ratio 2:1<br>
52nd lvl:  Lure of Frost <br>
DD Cold 640: mana 260 ratio 2.5:1<br>
55th lvl: Lure of Flame<br>
DD Fire 1000: mana 360 ratio 2.75:1<br>
58th lvl: Lure of Lightning<br>
DD Magic 1360: mana 450 ratio 3:1<br>
60th lvl Bane Spells<br>
DD Magic 2000: mana 400 ratio 5:1<br>
limited targets<br>
<br>
Flames await :-))<br>
<br>
